Introduction¶

The National Instant Criminal Background Check System (NICS) is a United States system for determining if prospective firearms or explosives buyers' name and birth year match those of a person who is not eligible to buy.

After a prospective buyer completes the appropriate form, the holder of a Federal Firearms License (FFL) initiates the background check by phone or computer. Most checks are determined within minutes, but the FBI has up to three business days to make a determination. After that, the transfer may legally proceed anyway.

The data comes from the FBI's National Instant Criminal Background Check System. The NICS is used by to determine whether a prospective buyer is eligible to buy firearms or explosives. Gun shops call into this system to ensure that each customer does not have a criminal record or isn’t otherwise ineligible to make a purchase. The data has been supplemented with state level data from census.gov.

The NICS data is found in one sheet of an .xlsx file ('gun_data.csv'). It contains the number of firearm checks by month, state, and type. The U.S. census data is found in a .csv file('us_census_data1.csv'). It contains several variables at the state level. Most variables just have one data point per state (2016), but a few have data for more than one year.

The data raises so many questions and can be analysed in many different angles. I chose to answer the below questions:

  1. How total gun purchase changed in the US over years?
  2. How is the average monthly distribution of Gnn purchase in the US?
  3. How the purchase of different types of guns changed in the US over years?
  4. How purchase of different types of guns is distributed among US States?
  5. Is there a relationship between gun purchase and human race in 2006?
  6. How close is the change in population to the change in Gun purchase between 2010 and 2016 in the US?
  7. How close is the change in population to the change in Gun purchase between 2010 and 2016 in "every state" in the US?
  8. What is the ratio of the change in gun buying to the change in population?
  9. How is the difference in purchase in every state between 2016 and 2010?

5. Flipping my dataframe

I need to flip the data frame so i get the states names in the rows not columns heads. To do that, first i need to define the index as the Fact column. so i make sure the values will be the column heads. Otherwise, i'll have another row with a numeric index on top of that. 3. How purchase of different types of guns changed in the US over years?¶

How is the overall trend for different types of guns? Was the change in purchase a drastic one for the different types? What is the more popular type of guns in recent years? Is the change in buying

In [121]:
# Calculating the final total number of every type and all types together 
handgun = df_gun['handgun'].sum()
long_gun = df_gun['long_gun'].sum()
other = df_gun['other'].sum()
multiple = df_gun['new_multiple'].sum()
everything = handgun + long_gun + other
I will be distributing the value of multiple to other typs.¶

To do that:

  • I'll be taking the proportion of every type from the total and using that proportion to get the number of every type in "new_mutltiple"
  • After getting the amount of every type in "new_multiple", I will be adding the amount of that type to it, then calculate the proportion of that type from the total
In [122]:
df_gun['handgun_prop'] = (((((df_gun['handgun']/everything)*100)*df_gun['new_multiple']/100)+df_gun['handgun'])/df_gun['total'])*100
df_gun['long_gun_prop'] = (((((df_gun['long_gun']/everything)*100)*df_gun['new_multiple']/100)+df_gun['long_gun'])/df_gun['total'])*100
df_gun['other_prop'] = (((((df_gun['other']/everything)*100)*df_gun['new_multiple']/100)+df_gun['other'])/df_gun['total'])*100
In [123]:
#taking the mean of all gun types purchase proportions and filtering by year
df_prop = df_gun.groupby('year')[['handgun_prop', 'long_gun_prop', 'other_prop']].mean()

Results: According to the data and graph, long_guns started really high in early years, they show a slight almost consistent decrease over the years. While handguns started low, almost have the proportion of long gun, they show a consistent and gradual increase to beat other types in recent years.

Other types show very low amounts from early years, around 3rd the proportion of handguns, they kept an almost stable numbers until 2009, where they dropped to almost the half, and even more on 2010. although they show some increase in recent years, but it's still didn't beat the 2009 numbers.

From the total guns purchases, the proportion of handguns in the last couple of years is the highest, and although long gun are still quite popular, they show a consistent decrease that might continue to coming years.

Conclusions¶

Limitations:

  • Assuming that all gun stors have a good quality and were commited to add entries for all purchases, this is the only data we had, the private sale is incomplete, also it doesn't include under-the-table purchases.

  • The census data only includes registered population, there are many people in the US that are not registered

  • The data in both datasets is not complete, some years are missing, there are so many null values even if the years with the 12 months.

  • The census data doesn't include all states.

  • There was some inconsistencies in the data format, i had to assume a certain format based on intuition.

  • The data had some outliers that i decided to include in my analysis

  • There are not enough facts to make a strong correlation to show that the change in one variable is solely affected by the change in the other one.

With the limitation in the data i had, and based on my analysis, these are my "TENTATIVE" findings:¶

Overall, the data shows an increase in number of guns purchased in the US. On average, the highest number of purchese was done on December, while May, June and july have the least number.

The data shows that in previous years, the number of long gun purchases was higher than any other type, then it started to slightly decrease. While handgun purchase shows a gradual increase to beat long guns purchase in 2015 and 2016.

The purchase in every state has changed over years. The total year purchase for every state shows Iowa has the highest number, while it's one of the lowest in recent years (2010 to 2016) same for North Carolina then Nebraska While Pennsylvania still keeps a high number in gun purchase over the years.

Looking at different gun types purchase in the states, Florida and Massachusetts are the highest in handgun buying. While Hawaii shows the highest in buying other types of guns. As for long gun, Iowa has the highest number then comes North Carolina, Nebraska and Pennsylvania.

The data shows that Gun purchase is compatible with the percentage of African American, Asian, and Hispanic or Latino in the US. While it shows negative correlation with the percentage of white, Hawaiian, Pacific Islander and Native Indian, Alaska.

The data suggests that the change in the growth rate for gun purchase over the US between the years 2010 and 2016 is way higher than that of the population for the same years.

According to the data, some states like Delaware, California, Massachusetts shows a very high change in gun purchase. While others, like Iowa and Nebraska, have a negative change, it might be that people are buying less Guns in 2016 than they used to in 2010, but we can state it as a fact without more data to confirm it.

Some states, has a negative ratio due to a recorded negative population change. While others have a high ratio, due to the recorded low population growth rate change and high gun purchase increase.
